                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If I where to Re-envision the Enchanter Class 
<br />
 
<br />
SOE has put forward that they want to re-envision the classes.  I thought -- if they can do it, why can't I?  At the worst, it's a mental exercise, and maybe some useful ideas will fall out. 
<br />
 
<br />
Mana regen and other 'passive' buff power: 
<br />
The first thing I'd do is reduce the marginal effectiveness of mana regen abilities, as well as other passive buff abilities. 
<br />
 
<br />
This is important: when a class gets alot of it's power from boring passive abilities, the class is either less fun than it should be, or overpowered. 
<br />
 
<br />
Halve the amount of mana regen from buffs (you can make buffs generate mana only every 2nd tick), and give people additional 'free' mana regen to keep the top end unchanged.  A standing mana regen bonus of (level * (main_casting_stat+5))/700 would give a L 70 365 int caster 37 more mana/tick, or 6.5/tick more in a full raid buff situation. 
<br />
 
<br />
I would actually propose leaving 'active' mana regen alone (SK tap, Necro tap, BST AA, mod rods), while making the passive mana regen half as effective, as detailed above. 
<br />
 
<br />
(necro lich form at the highest end would lose 10 mana/tick, equivalent to the amount lost from C6, the buff it doesn't stack with.  The reduction would be scaled down to previous buffs, paired up with the equivalent enchanter-mind buff of the same era.) 
<br />
 
<br />
Self-haste effects (20% to 30%) should be added to DPS melee classes. 
<br />
 
<br />
Give SK a disease-based group haste-tap (25% slow on target, 30% haste on group).  Paladins already have a self-haste.  Give warriors, rogues and monks endurance-costing haste buffs (10% at L 50, 15% at L 60, 20% at L 70).  Add in 25% haste to the ranger post-66 skin buff line. 
<br />
 
<br />
40% haste items+25% spell haste = 65% haste, which makes haste buffs up DPS by 21%.  This makes haste buffing (a passive ability) less important, freeing up power for fun active abilities from the buffing classes. 
<br />
 
<br />
Possibly do something similar to priest HP buffs. 
<br />

<br />
Defence: 
<br />
Enchanters should be an add-control class.  In todays game you can either eliminate adds with pull control, or control them in camp.  Control in camp means getting hit. 
<br />
 
<br />
Enchanters should specialize in in-camp crowd control, and hence they need to be acceptable -- nay, I would even say exceptional -- at getting hit. 
<br />
 
<br />
Back in the day this was dealt with by Enchanter PBAOE stuns, and the fact that creatures had no danger of single-rounding players: damage was about healer mana and aggro, not about instant death.  This has changed. 
<br />
 
<br />
This also can't be dealt with by aggro-bleed abilities, like boggle or doppleganger.  Redirecting an add from the crowd controller to a random member of the group (often the healer) results in group wipes.  These abilities have their place, but that cannot be the core of enchanter defence if enchanters are to be viewed as effective add control. 
<br />
 
<br />
So, to this end, I have a number of proposals: 
<br />
First, +% self-rune foci should be added to the game.  5% to 50% (non-random) and higher.  These foci should work on any self-only rune, making it useful to necros wizards and enchanters (but mainly enchanters). 
<br />
 
<br />
Every 5% of rune focus works out to 100 extra enchanter rune and 50 extra necro/wizard rune (roughly). 
<br />
 
<br />
Alternatively, two kinds of rune foci could be added: +% on self-rune spells, and a stacking 'combat modifier' like +% on runes that land on you. 
<br />
 
<br />
Secondly, rework "Mind over Matter".  Remove the reuse timer, place the buff in the short-buff-box, remove the hit count, and change it's ratio to 3 damage per point of mana at L 3 (2 and 2.5 at L 1 and 2 respectfully).  Have MoM only work on damage that gets through runes. 
<br />
 
<br />
(<span style="font-style: italic">edit: addition</span>)
<br />
This means MoM would be up whenever the enchanter wanted it up.  For the most part, I suspect enchanters would keep it up at all times -- which means enchanter mitigation for short-burst damage is as good as a tank's, but they can't keep this mitigation up for long periods of time.
<br />

<br />
Thirdly, return the enchanter PB line to a decent state. 
<br />
The OOW PBAOE stun should have a 1.5 to 1.0 casting time: it is supposed to be cast when creatures are beating on you, 2.0 seconds is silly.  Add in a L 66+ PBAOE mez spell: having 2 PBAOE defence spells is tactically important for when one is resisted. 
<br />

<br />
Together, these changes make enchanters good tanks against spike DPS from monsters.  At the same time, sustained enchanter tanking isn't viable.  Even with +50% efficiency, arcane rune on an enchanter isn't efficient enough to tank.  And the 3 damage:1 mana ratio of improved MoM is laughable compared to current heals, even ignoring tank mitigation advantages over a cloth class. 
<br />
 
<br />
However, using these abilities, enchanters can be relied upon to deal with an add.  Resists make the encounter more costly, which means the enchanter may need a break, but don't kill the enchanter quicker than they can be healed. 
<br />
 
<br />
This results in crowd control abilities whose cost increases with mob DPS.  It also retroactively makes high-mana gear (typical enchanter itemization) good for crowd control purposes. 
<br />
 
<br />
Mezzing: 
<br />
The core of an incamp add-control class is mezzing.  Right now, mezzes are designed so that you need a particular mez against particular content, and the costs of the mezzes go up. 
<br />
 
<br />
This means that an enchanter without the particular mez spell is incapable of acting as an effective add control class.  And it is a very discontinuous effect: either the enchanter is fine, or incapable. 
<br />
 
<br />
I would hold that this isn't a good design feature around a core competency of a class. 
<br />
 
<br />
Change mez caps so they are 'softcaps'.  Every level higher than the softcap, the duration of the mez should be reduced by 2 or 3 ticks, or some other amount.  (for example, 1 tick for the first level, 2 for the 2nd, 3 for the 3rd, resulting in: 
<br />
+0: -0 total ticks (9 to 13 tick mez, depending on gear/AA) 
<br />
+1: -1 total ticks (8 to 12 tick mez, depending on gear/AA) 
<br />
+2: -3 total ticks (6 to 10 tick mez, depending on gear/AA) 
<br />
+3: -6 total ticks (3 to 7 tick mez, depending on gear/AA) 
<br />
+4: -10 total ticks (0 to 3 tick mez, depending on gear/AA) 
<br />
+5: -15 total ticks (0 tick mez, regardless of gear/AA)) 
<br />
 
<br />
Or, each spell could code the amount of level-decay in the base2 field.) 
<br />
 
<br />
Second, make debuff-duration extending items be non-random on mez spells, and round up.  For a 9 tick mez: 
<br />
+1 to 11% extension: +1 tick 
<br />
12% to 22% extension: +2 tick 
<br />
23% to 33% extension: +3 tick 
<br />
 
<br />
A L 70 enchanter trying to mez L 73 mobs using Bliss would be out of luck, but with top end gear, AAs, and lots of effort they could handle L 71 or 72 mobs. 
<br />
 
<br />
Third, bring some variety into the enchanter's mez lineup.  I don't mean unresistable mezzes. 
<br />
 
<br />
Fast mezzes: 1.0 casting time, 4 or 5 tick base duration. 
<br />
Long mezzes: 4.0 casting time, 15+ tick base duration. 
<br />
PBAOE mezzes: 1.5 casting time, 1 tick base duration. 
<br />
 
<br />
Charm: 
<br />
The first thing to note is, the defence improvements above change the risk v reward of charming massively. 
<br />
 
<br />
Charming a weak mob that turns into an add is far more acceptable when single adds are safely controllable by enchanters. 
<br />
 
<br />
The coded damage cap on mobs has gotten rid of most of the reasons to have a lower charm cap than a mez cap. 
<br />
 
<br />
Possibly the aggro generated on the enchanter from a broken charm should be ramped up, reducing the danger to other members of the raid. 
<br />
 
<br />
A combat charm, with a resist modifier, short duration, and fast casting time (3.0 or faster), would make using charm as a form of raid or pull CC interesting.  Some enchanters where using CoD in such a way back with it had a -50 resist mod in early PoP. 
<br />
 
<br />
Other classes: 
<br />
Give tanks (and rangers, the light tank) "Mind over Matter" type abilities that burn endurance and/or mana, at 20% to 33% of incoming damage rates, and a cost:hp ratio that makes them lose mana/endurance at about the same rate as enchanters (including mitigation costs) and have about the same unhealed survivability.  This makes offtanking adds more viable. 
<br />
 
<br />
Spread out mez a bit.  Give necros a screaming-terror like general-purpose mez.  Give shamans and clerics an undead mez, druids and beastlords an animal mez, druids/mages/rangers a summoned mez. 
<br />
A 4.5 casting time (hasteable to 3.0), 6.0 recast time, 5 tick duration, -0 resist modifier, L 71 cap (with the above level-cap softening code), with target type restrictions. 
<br />
 
<br />
This means there will be 3 classes with some mezzing ability on all mobs, and on animal/undead/summoned mobs there will be 5-6 classes.  With enchanter defence improvements, they will still be a very good choice for mez-based crowd control. 
<br />
 
<br />
In summary: 
<br />
None of the above abilities provide the enchanter with more DPS. 
<br />
None of the above abilities allow the enchanter to sustainably tank content better than a tank. 
<br />
 
<br />
What they do do is make an enchanter better at doing their niche job: controlling adds in camp.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">edit: snipped an incomplete section on priest HP buffs, and added a clarifying paragraph to MoM.</span></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Yakk on Thu Feb 24, 2005 10:47 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
