                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Unmei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">You obviously didn't read very carefully.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No need to be snooty (pfft) but you are correct, the paragraph that described the conversion with the figures made my eyes glaze over and I misunderstood it.
<br />

<br />
Now that I understand, it does have it's merits. Two things though, they would have to be careful to scale it correctly. The difference between the max regen a level 20 can attain and a level 70 is quite a large margin. Deciding exactly how much should become innate could be tricky. Second, if you shorten buff timers in attempt to attract the buffers into the group, you may end up with the opposite affect where folks decide to just go without. That would be hard to predict which way it may go...of course, there may be a nice balance between folks going without, and specifically seeking out the buffers. That would be nice for a change.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I really don't follow you.  How is a mana inefficient (relative to heals) Rune going to radically change the game?  Enchanters still mitigate poorly, they just have more chances to use their own mana pool to survive it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
If you up the rune amount with a focus, you do improve it's efficiency. I still believe that a rune is much better at dealing with spike damage than a heal, so, in some situations, combining the two would (and this is just my theory) exponentionally increase the power of the group/raid. I could be wrong, but I really feel that is what would happen.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Becoming a tank or a healer for a short time sounds like a balance issue to -me-. o.o</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I suppose so, but I still kinda like the idea. Say you have a pull where there is no need for chanter skills. You could decide to take on the abilities of the pulled mob for a short bit (heavily modified of course) and contribute in a different way. If the mob was a healer, you would become dps that has a decent heal. If it were a necro, you could become dps with a decent dot. If it were just melee, you could become a decent melee. Say you have a 3 pull, and you CC it down, but on the third mob, the tank drops. You quick change to the mob type, take over tanking (obviously not as well as the real tank) and save the day.
<br />

<br />
Not sure why this idea appeals to me, but I just think it would be neat.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">That is all I have to say about that! - Forest Gump</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
